TOPICS COVERED (SUPPORT VECTOR MACHINE (SVM) FOR CLASSIFICATION)
Introduction to Support Vector Machine (SVM)

The training session began with an introduction to Support Vector Machine (SVM), a powerful supervised Machine Learning algorithm used for both classification and regression tasks. Learned that SVM is mainly used for classification problems and works by finding the optimal decision boundary (hyperplane) that best separates different classes of data.

The trainer explained that SVM aims to maximize the margin between different classes, making the model more robust and capable of achieving high prediction accuracy even with complex datasets.

Discussed real-world applications such as image classification, face recognition, text categorization, medical diagnosis, and handwriting recognition.

Understanding Hyperplanes

Studied the concept of a Hyperplane, which is the decision boundary used by SVM to separate different classes.

Learned that:

A hyperplane divides data into different classes.
In two-dimensional data, the hyperplane is represented as a straight line.
In higher-dimensional data, it becomes a plane or higher-dimensional surface.

Understood how the best hyperplane maximizes the separation between different classes.

Support Vectors

Received a detailed explanation of Support Vectors, the most important data points in an SVM model.

Learned that:

Support vectors are the data points closest to the decision boundary.
They determine the position and orientation of the hyperplane.
Removing support vectors significantly changes the model.

Discussed why SVM focuses only on support vectors rather than the entire dataset.

Margin and Maximum Margin Classifier

Studied the concept of Margin, which is the distance between the hyperplane and the nearest data points.

Learned that:

A larger margin generally improves model generalization.
SVM always tries to maximize the margin.
Maximum margin reduces the risk of overfitting.

Compared narrow and wide margins using graphical examples.

Kernel Functions

Received an introduction to Kernel Functions, which enable SVM to solve non-linear classification problems.

Studied different types of kernels:

Linear Kernel
Suitable for linearly separable datasets.
Faster and computationally efficient.
Polynomial Kernel
Captures polynomial relationships between features.
Useful for moderately complex datasets.
Radial Basis Function (RBF) Kernel
One of the most commonly used kernels.
Handles highly non-linear datasets effectively.
Sigmoid Kernel
Similar to neural network activation functions.
Used in specific classification tasks.

Compared the advantages and limitations of each kernel type.

Linear vs Non-Linear Classification

Learned the difference between linearly separable and non-linearly separable datasets.

Discussed how:

Linear SVM works when data can be separated by a straight line.
Kernel functions transform non-linear data into higher dimensions where linear separation becomes possible.

Practiced understanding different data distributions through graphical examples.

